`getTerritory(int x, int y)`:
- If `board[y][x]` is not ' ', return empty set.
- Otherwise, perform BFS/DFS to find all connected empty intersections.
- While traversing, keep track of adjacent stones ('B' or 'W').
- Return the set of points.

`getTerritoryOwner(int x, int y)`:
- Get territory points.
- If empty, return `Player.NONE`.
- Check adjacent stones of the territory.
- If only 'B' stones touch it, owner is `BLACK`.
- If only 'W' stones touch it, owner is `WHITE`.
- If both or neither, owner is `NONE`.

`getTerritories()`:
- Iterate over all points on the board.
- If a point is empty and not yet visited, compute its territory.
- Determine owner.
- Add to map.
- Return map.

Let's refine `getTerritory`:
```java
Set<Point> getTerritory(int x, int y) {
    if (x < 0 || x >= width || y < 0 || y >= height) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid coordinate");
    }
    if (board[y][x] != ' ') {
        return new HashSet<>();
    }
    
    Set<Point> territory = new HashSet<>();
    Set<Point> visited = new HashSet<>();
    Queue<Point> queue = new ArrayDeque<>();
    
    queue.add(new Point(x, y));
    visited.add(new Point(x, y));
    
    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
        Point p = queue.poll();
        territory.add(p);
        
        int[] dx = {0, 0, 1, -1};
        int[] dy = {1, -1, 0, 0};
        
        for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
            int nx = p.x + dx[i];
            int ny = p.y + dy[i];
            if (nx >= 0 && nx < width && ny >= 0 && ny < height) {
                Point neighbor = new Point(nx, ny);
                if (!visited.contains(neighbor)) {
                    if (board[ny][nx] == ' ') {
                        visited.add(neighbor);
                        queue.add(neighbor);
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return territory;
}
```

